	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=16228&mid=103412515983425>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=16228&mid=103412515983425>RE: Leveling</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=16228&mid=103412515983425#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Oct 8th 9:16 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=100518><span id= >Meirril</span></a><br><span id=notbold>205 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>You more or less said exactly what you need to do to level. Basicaly, don't do anything that won't generate xp and you'll gain levels. Sounds stupid but it's the basic truth. A little more useful is to ask others of your class and slightly higher level where they were hunting at your level. Don't ask people that are WAY above your level, Eq changes and the area they recomend may not be the same as it was back when they were your level (like it may be a great zone for groups, but solo xp there stinks and nobody goes there any more. Or maybe it got revamped and you'd last long enough to get too far into the zone to retrive your own corpse. Take CT as an example of a revamped zone). Also explore websights and threads that talk about your classes abilities. Druids at 34 gain the spells that allow them to quad kite. At 36 they finaly have the mana to quad kite even if they arn't twinked. What do you need to know to quad kite? A few things. 1: you need lots of room to quad kite. Means you need somewhere you can run without getting a lot of adds. 2: you can only do 4 mobs at a time with your AoE. So, only get 4 mobs at most (and its a waste of mana getting less than 4.). 3: Use Ensnare. You'll need to use alot of time getting 4 mobs together, the 10 min duration of Ensnare is what makes quad kitting work, not the improved damage of druid AoE spells. 4: The lightning based AoE has an area of effect of 1. Basicaly, you need to run around the mobs your kitting until they are touching each other, then your AoE will hit all 4. 5: Picking mobs to quad kite is the hardest part of quad kitting after you get a little practice. You need mobs with low HP for their level. Usualy these are animals with insane damage output, but your not going to melee them so who cares? 6:Always have gate and a finishing spell mem'ed. If you get an add you MIGHT have the extra mana to handle it. Or a little extra med time to get that last AoE off. Maybe, better to be safe than sorry. Also, out of most quads you'll usualy AoE 3 of them to death, and the one that resisted a few times is left running for his life. Use a more efficient spell to finish him off. 7: Last thing to remember is that Quad Kitting realy dosen't work in the old world (Antonica, Fadewer, Euradin) because the old mobs run even when they have friends helping them. <br>My suggestion to a level 36 or so druid learning to quadkite is to pick on the Ulthork Hunters in EW. Great xp and a nice clear area to quad in. They even have (some) loot!<br><br>Incase anyone read this far, my last suggestion is to go for levels instead of loot. While good equipment helps ALOT to get levels, it isn't as good as another level. Don't do anything that will significanly slow down your xp. When you get to a fairly decent level (45+) start worrying about equipment when your making enough plat without realy trying to buy a few peices here and there. By the time you hit 50 you'll have all that equipment you'd been looking for earlier and working on mobs that drop the stuff you realy wanted and getting xp for it.</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Meirril, Fennin Ro</td></tr>
